# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: argentine-national-observatory
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:argentine-national-observatory/argentine-national-observatory] The **Argentine National Observatory**, today the **Astronomical Observatory of Córdoba**, was founded on 24 October 1871, by Argentine president Domingo F.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/argentine-national-observatory] Sarmiento and the North American astronomer Benjamin Apthorp Gould.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/argentine-national-observatory] Its creation was the beginning of astronomical studies in Argentina.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/argentine-national-observatory] Sarmiento was representing his country in the United States, he had the opportunity to meet pioneering astronomer Benjamin Apthorp Gould, who was very interested in traveling to Argentina in order to study the stellar south hemisphere.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/argentine-national-observatory] Once Sarmiento was installed as President of Argentina, he invited Gould to travel to Argentina, in 1869, to provide his full support to organize an observatory.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/argentine-national-observatory] The same night of the inauguration of the Astronomical Observatory of Córdoba, Gould began with the naked eye, and later with the aid of small binoculars, a map of the southern sky, recording more than 7000 stars, which was published under the name of *Uranometría Argentina*.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/argentine-national-observatory] This work by Gould, Miles Rock and others formalized the southern constellations which were not as well documented as the northern ones.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/argentine-national-observatory] He remained as director of the observatory until 1885, when he returned to the United States.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/argentine-national-observatory] The first stellar photographs in the world – hundreds of sheets of open star clusters – were taken at this observatory.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/argentine-national-observatory] This helped to determine the exact position of each star.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/argentine-national-observatory] Gould published the results in the *Catálogo de zonas estelares* (1884), the first systematic and large-scale astronomy book, including more than 70,000 stars of the southern hemisphere, and the Argentinian General Catalog, which contains about 35,000 stars.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/argentine-national-observatory] As part of the Córdoba Astronomical Observatory, the Meteorological Office was created by Sarmiento at Gould's suggestion in 1872, and is now known as the National Meteorological Service.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/argentine-national-observatory] The national network of meteorological stations and geomagnetic observatories was established in 1873.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/argentine-national-observatory] The Bosque Alegre Astrophysics Station is located about 30 miles southwest of Cordoba at an altitude of 1200 meters (3,937-ft) in the Sierras Chicas.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/argentine-national-observatory] The observatory was integral to the development of Argentine and Latin American Astrophysics.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/argentine-national-observatory] For example, the Atlas of Austral Galaxies by J.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/argentine-national-observatory] The 61-inch (1.54-meter) Great Reflector was the concept of the director of the Argentine National Observatory, Charles Dillon Perrine, who assumed the directorship in 1909.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/argentine-national-observatory] He had experience with the 36-in Crossley Reflector at Lick Observatory from 1900 to 1909.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/argentine-national-observatory] In 1912 the National Government approved Perrine's proposal to construct this telescope, equal to the largest in the world at that time.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/argentine-national-observatory] It would remain the largest in South America until 1981 when a larger one was built in Brazil.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/argentine-national-observatory] The mount and dome were contracted to Warner and Swasey of Cleveland, Ohio, USA.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/argentine-national-observatory] The glass block for the mirror was ordered from Saint-Gobain of France, completed in Dec.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/argentine-national-observatory] 1912, and delivered to Argentina in early 1913.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/argentine-national-observatory] Due to the high price asked by George W.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/argentine-national-observatory] Ritchey (USA) to figure (shape and polish) the glass into a mirror, Perrine decided to have the highly skilled staff technician, James Mulvey, do the work at the observatory itself in a purpose-built optics laboratory.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/argentine-national-observatory] This experience put Argentina at the forefront in this field.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/argentine-national-observatory] Mulvey, the First World War, the rebuilding of the Observatory in the city of Córdoba, political challenges, and national economic limitations significantly delayed the project.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/argentine-national-observatory] In 1936, Perrine retired, having selected the site, constructed the station buildings, and assembled the telescope mount, but the mirror was not yet complete.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/argentine-national-observatory] Aguilar and JJ Nissen, director of the National Observatory, assumed responsibility and the mirror was sent for completion to the Fecker optician in the US.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/argentine-national-observatory] At that time, the telescope was the third largest in the world.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/argentine-national-observatory] The first Argentine astrophysicist Enrique Gaviola went to the US in 1939 to receive the mirror.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/argentine-national-observatory] Sadly, Fecker, even with its well-known expertise, could not complete the mirror.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/argentine-national-observatory] Gaviola took control of the configuration (shaping and polishing) and completed it.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/argentine-national-observatory] Finally, on July 5, 1942, after 33 years of work, the Astrophysical Station was inaugurated. “This Astrophysical Station was born in the optimistic and courageous mind of Charles Dillon Perrine, director of the Cordoba Observatory from 1909 to 1936.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/argentine-national-observatory] Perrine dedicated the best energies of many years of his life to the realization in the matter of his daring dream.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/argentine-national-observatory] He had triumphs and defeats, successes and failures.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/argentine-national-observatory] " Words by Enrique Gaviola, inauguration speech of the Bosque Alegre Astrophysical Station, July 5, 1942.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/argentine-national-observatory] A 20-in (76-cm) telescope was obtained by Director Perrine and figured by Mulvey as practice before figuring the larger 61-inch (1.54-meter) mirror.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/argentine-national-observatory] It was the “first large reflecting telescope, designed, built entirely in Argentina (1913-18), and used with success”.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/argentine-national-observatory] Later it was named the "Perrine" after C.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/argentine-national-observatory] Perrine, the Director from 1909 to 1936.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/argentine-national-observatory] It was first used at the Cordoba Observatory, then because of urban light pollution in the mid-1970's, it was moved to the High Altitude Station of the Félix Aguilar Astronomical Observatory in the province of San Juan.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/argentine-national-observatory] On November 18, 2011, the "Perrine" was re-located and installed in its own dome at Bosque Alegre.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/argentine-national-observatory] At this time the "Perrine" is the second largest telescope at Bosque Alegre and the fourth largest in Argentina.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/argentine-national-observatory] It was put to work immediately and continues to be used to do the necessary validation of discoveries of celestial bodies located in different parts of the sky.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/benjamin-apthorp-gould] He was born in Boston, Massachusetts, the son of Lucretia Dana (Goddard) and Benjamin Apthorp Gould, the principal of Boston Latin School, which the younger Gould attended.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/benjamin-apthorp-gould] The poet Hannah Flagg Gould was his aunt.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/benjamin-apthorp-gould] He studied at Harvard College under Benjamin Peirce, graduating in 1844.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/benjamin-apthorp-gould] He studied mathematics and astronomy under C.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/benjamin-apthorp-gould] Gauss at Göttingen, Germany, during which time he published approximately 20 papers on the observation and motion of comets and asteroids.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/benjamin-apthorp-gould] (he was the first American to receive this degree in astronomy) he toured European observatories asking for advice on what could be done to further astronomy as a professional science in the U.S.A.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/benjamin-apthorp-gould] The main advice he received was to start a professional journal modeled after what was then the world's leading astronomical publication, the *Astronomische Nachrichten*.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/benjamin-apthorp-gould] Gould returned to America in 1848 and from 1852 to 1867 worked in the United States Coast Survey, where he worked in geodetic astronomy and was in charge of the longitude department.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/benjamin-apthorp-gould] He developed and organized the service, was one of the first to determine longitudes by telegraphic means, and employed the Atlantic cable in 1866 to establish accurate longitude-relations between Europe and America.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/benjamin-apthorp-gould] One of his assistants and life-long mentee was Seth Carlo Chandler, who went on to discover the Chandler wobble.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/benjamin-apthorp-gould] After his return to Cambridge, Massachusetts, Gould started the *Astronomical Journal* in 1849, which he published until 1861.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/benjamin-apthorp-gould] He resumed publication in 1885 and it is still published today.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/benjamin-apthorp-gould] From 1855 to 1859 he acted as director of the Dudley Observatory at Albany, New York, and in 1859 published a discussion of the places and proper motions of circumpolar stars to be used as standards by the United States Coast Survey.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/benjamin-apthorp-gould] In 1861 he undertook the enormous task of preparing for publication the records of astronomical observations made at the United States Naval Observatory since 1850.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/benjamin-apthorp-gould] In 1851 Gould suggested numbering asteroids in their order of discovery, and placing this number in a disk (circle) as the generic symbol of an asteroid.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/benjamin-apthorp-gould] That same year, he was elected as a member to the American Philosophical Society.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/benjamin-apthorp-gould] In 1864 he was admitted to the Massachusetts Society of the Cincinnati to represent his grandfather Captain Benjamin Gould.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/benjamin-apthorp-gould] In the 1890s he became an early member of the Massachusetts Society of the Sons of the American Revolution.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/benjamin-apthorp-gould] Appointed in 1862 actuary to the United States Sanitary Commission, he issued in 1869 an important volume of *Investigations in the Military and Anthropological Statistics of American Soldiers*.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/benjamin-apthorp-gould] This study, informed by Gould's commitment to race science, purported to construct typologies of Black and Indigenous bodies, in particular.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/benjamin-apthorp-gould] In 1864 he fitted up a private observatory at Cambridge, Massachusetts, and undertook in 1868, on behalf of the Argentine republic, to organize a national observatory at Córdoba.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/benjamin-apthorp-gould] In 1871 he became the first director of the Argentine National Observatory (today, Observatorio Astronómico de Córdoba of the National University of Córdoba).
[src:argentine-national-observatory/benjamin-apthorp-gould] While there, he and four assistants (including Miles Rock) extensively mapped the southern hemisphere skies using newly developed photometric methods.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/benjamin-apthorp-gould] On June 1, 1884, he made the last definite sighting of the Great Comet of 1882.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/benjamin-apthorp-gould] The need of astronomers for good weather prediction spurred Gould to collaborate with Argentine colleagues to develop the Argentine National Weather Service, the first in South America.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/benjamin-apthorp-gould] Rutherfurd's photographs of the Pleiades in 1866 entitle him to rank as a pioneer in the use of the camera as an instrument of precision; and he secured at Córdoba 1400 negatives of southern star clusters, the reduction of which occupied the closing years of his life.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/benjamin-apthorp-gould] He remained in Argentina until 1885, when he returned to Cambridge, Massachusetts.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/benjamin-apthorp-gould] He received the Gold Medal of the Royal Astronomical Society in 1883 and the James Craig Watson Medal in 1887.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/benjamin-apthorp-gould] Astronomers continue to investigate the astrophysics of a large scale feature of the Milky Way to which he called their attention in 1877, and honor him with its name, The Gould Belt.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/benjamin-apthorp-gould] A crater on the Moon is named after him.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/benjamin-apthorp-gould] Gould was elected a member of the American Antiquarian Society in 1892.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/benjamin-apthorp-gould] He died at Cambridge, Massachusetts in 1896.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/benjamin-apthorp-gould] In 1874, while in Argentina with his assistants, Gould completed his greatest work, the *Uranometria Argentina*, consisting of an atlas published in 1877 and catalog in 1879, for which he received in 1883 the gold medal of the Royal Astronomical Society.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/benjamin-apthorp-gould] The atlas introduced the system of defining constellation boundaries along lines of right ascension and declination, which was officially adopted by the International Astronomical Union for the whole sky in 1930.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/benjamin-apthorp-gould] The catalog assigned Gould designations to all bright stars within 100 degrees of the south celestial pole in a manner similar to what Flamsteed had earlier done for the northern hemisphere.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/benjamin-apthorp-gould] An updated version, to which late 20th century data have been appended to the complete information for all stars in the original Uranometria Argentina, is available at www.uranometriaargentina.com/.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/benjamin-apthorp-gould] Gould followed his *Uranometria Argentina* with a zone-catalogue of 73,160 stars (1884), and a general catalogue (1885) compiled from meridian observations of 32,448 stars.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/benjamin-apthorp-gould] Alice Bache Gould (1868–1953), a mathematician, philanthropist, and historian, was one of his five children.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/charles-dillon-perrine] In 1897 he was awarded the Lalande Prize and gold medal by the Paris Academy of Sciences given each year "to the person who makes the most outstanding observation ... to further the progress of Astronomy, in France or elsewhere.".
[src:argentine-national-observatory/charles-dillon-perrine] He served as president of the Astronomical Society of the Pacific in 1902, was elected an Associate of the Royal Astronomical Society in 1904, and was awarded the gold medal of the Mexican Astronomical Society in 1905.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/charles-dillon-perrine] In the same year he received the degree of Doctor of Sciences (honorary) from Santa Clara College (today Santa Clara University).
[src:argentine-national-observatory/charles-dillon-perrine] A crater on the far side of the Moon was named in his honor in 1970.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/charles-dillon-perrine] Charles was born in Steubenville, Ohio, the son of Peter, a Methodist minister, and Elizabeth (McCauley) Perrine.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/charles-dillon-perrine] He was a descendant of Daniel Perrin, "The Huguenot", and Maria Thorel whose marriage was the first (European) recorded in Elizabethtown, New Jersey, (Feb 18, 1666).
[src:argentine-national-observatory/charles-dillon-perrine] Following high school graduation in 1884, he moved to Alameda, California in about 1886 and worked as a bookkeeper at Armour & Co., a meat-packing business in San Francisco.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/charles-dillon-perrine] Interested in photography and astronomy from an early age, and unable to afford a college education, "he nevertheless looked forward to engaging in astronomical work".
[src:argentine-national-observatory/charles-dillon-perrine] Perrine responded to a general invitation to amateurs in astronomy and photography from E.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/charles-dillon-perrine] Holden, the Director of the newly established Lick Observatory (1888), to observe the total solar eclipse of January 1, 1889 in Northern California.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/charles-dillon-perrine] Perrine's report and photographs caught the attention of the Director who hired him as Secretary in 1893.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/charles-dillon-perrine] Holden agreed to Perrine's "fixed purpose of devoting his spare time to the study of astronomical and related subjects, by way of preparation for later observatory duties".
[src:argentine-national-observatory/charles-dillon-perrine] As his experience, skills, and discoveries grew he was promoted to Secretary and Assistant Astronomer (1895), Assistant Astronomer (1902), and Astronomer (1905).
[src:argentine-national-observatory/charles-dillon-perrine] From 1895 to 1902 Perrine discovered eight unexpected and four periodic comets including the co-discovery of the lost periodic comet 18D/Perrine-Mrkos in 1896 (see list below).
[src:argentine-national-observatory/charles-dillon-perrine] Antonín Mrkos later named the asteroid 6779 Perrine after him.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/charles-dillon-perrine] The lunar crater Perrine is also named after him.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/charles-dillon-perrine] In 1904-05 he discovered the sixth and seventh moons of Jupiter, today known as Himalia (December 3, 1904) and Elara (February 21, 1905) using telescopic photography (glass plate negatives) with the 36-inch Crossley Reflector which he had recently rebuilt.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/charles-dillon-perrine] At the time they were simply designated "Jupiter VI" and "Jupiter VII" and were given their present names in 1975.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/charles-dillon-perrine] The first certain observations of Jupiter's moons (I - IV) were those published by Galileo Galilei in 1610.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/charles-dillon-perrine] No additional moons were discovered until E.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/charles-dillon-perrine] Barnard observed Amalthea (Jupiter V) in 1892.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/charles-dillon-perrine] Perrine participated in four solar eclipse expeditions of the Lick Observatory: 1900 (Georgia, USA), 1901 (Sumatra), 1905 (Spain), and 1908 (Flint Island), and was in charge of the one sent to Sumatra.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/charles-dillon-perrine] Also in 1901, he and George Ritchey observed the apparent superluminal motion in the nebulosity surrounding Nova Persei 1901.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/charles-dillon-perrine] In 1909 he resigned from the Lick Observatory to accept the position of Director of the Argentine National Observatory (today, Observatorio Astronómico de Córdoba) at Cordoba, Argentina, a position which he held until his retirement in 1936 at age 69.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/charles-dillon-perrine] Perrine played an early role in the history of general relativity and tests of general relativity.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/charles-dillon-perrine] The Argentine National Observatory led by Perrine made the first attempt to test Albert Einstein's Theory of Relativity by observing the deflection of star light near the Sun at a total solar eclipse.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/charles-dillon-perrine] Perrine wrote, "The Cordoba Observatory made the first definite attempt to secure observations at an eclipse (that of 1912) for the relativity problem and that was done at the instigation of Dr.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/charles-dillon-perrine] Freundlich." Einstein, in 1905, had proposed his Theory of Special Relativity which predicted that gravity bent light.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/charles-dillon-perrine] In 1911 Einstein wrote, "It would be urgently wished that astronomers take up the question here raised (gravitational light deflection near the Sun),...".
[src:argentine-national-observatory/charles-dillon-perrine] Erwin Finlay-Freundlich, a German astronomer and mathematician, took up Einstein's challenge and contacted Perrine in 1911 and 1912 to ask if he would undertake a test of light deflection near the Sun.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/charles-dillon-perrine] Perrine agreed to add the test to his planned expedition to Cristina, Brazil to observe the total solar eclipse of October 10, 1912.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/charles-dillon-perrine] William Wallace Campbell, the Director of the Lick Observatory, recognizing that Perrine would likely be the most experienced eclipse observer, also encouraged him to pursue the test and loaned him Lick's eclipse camera lenses with which Perrine had previous eclipse experience while at Lick.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/charles-dillon-perrine] The Argentine National Observatory built the telescopes and readied the equipment at the observation site at Cristina, Brazil.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/charles-dillon-perrine] Unfortunately, steady rain made visibility and therefore the test impossible.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/charles-dillon-perrine] As Perrine put it, "We suffered a total eclipse instead of observing one".
[src:argentine-national-observatory/charles-dillon-perrine] While observational results were elusive in 1912, the expedition produced valuable instruments (telescopes, cameras, timers, etc.) and experience for the next eclipse in 1914 in Russia.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/charles-dillon-perrine] Three observatories would organize expeditions and include light deflection in their programs for 1914; the Argentine National Observatory (Perrine), the Lick Observatory (Campbell), and the Berlin-Babelsberg Observatory (Freundlich).
[src:argentine-national-observatory/charles-dillon-perrine] Perrine's photograph of the total solar eclipse of August 21, 1914 may have been the first taken with the intent and equipment to measure star light deflection near the Sun which effect was predicted by Einstein's Special Theory of Relativity in 1911.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/charles-dillon-perrine] Thin clouds obscured the eclipse just enough to prevent accurate star observation.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/charles-dillon-perrine] Perrine pioneered the study of astrophysics in Argentina and promoted the construction of the 60-inch/1.54 m reflecting telescope at Bosque Alegre which was completed in 1942 after his retirement in 1936.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/charles-dillon-perrine] It would remain the largest telescope in South America until 1981 when Brazil built a 63-inch reflector.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/charles-dillon-perrine] After retirement he lived first in Cordoba city and next in Villa General Mitre (originally and again Villa del Totoral) where he died.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/charles-dillon-perrine] He is buried in the Cementerio del Salvador (Cemetery of the Savior) formerly called the *Cementerio de Disidentes* (cemetery of dissidents/non-Catholics), in the city of Córdoba.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/crossley-reflector] The **Crossley telescope** is a 36-inch (910 mm) reflecting telescope located at Lick Observatory in the U.S. state of California.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/crossley-reflector] It was used between 1895 and 2010, and was donated to the observatory by Edward Crossley, its namesake.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/crossley-reflector] It was the largest glass reflecting telescope in the United States for several years after its recommissioning in California.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/crossley-reflector] Given to the Lick Observatory in 1895 by British politician Edward Crossley, it was rebuilt from the ground up as it was on a very flimsy mounting.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/crossley-reflector] It was last used in 2010 in the search for extra-solar planets but has been taken out of service due to budget cuts.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/crossley-reflector] The mirror, and some of the initial mounts, came from the 36-inch reflector originally mounted in Andrew Ainslie Common's backyard Ealing observatory.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/crossley-reflector] He had used it from 1879 to 1886 to prove the concept of long exposure astrophotography (recording objects too faint to be seen by the naked eye for the first time).
[src:argentine-national-observatory/crossley-reflector] Common sold it to Crossley who had it until 1895.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/crossley-reflector] The 36-inch A.A.Common mirror was made by George Calver for Common, and was ordered after Common wanted one bigger than the 18-inch reflecting telescope, which also had a mirror from Calver.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/crossley-reflector] Common completed this telescope by 1879, and went on to make a 60-inch telescope; he sold the 36-inch to Crossley.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/crossley-reflector] Crossley set the telescope up in Halifax, England in a new dome.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/crossley-reflector] Meanwhile, at the Lick Observatory in California, Edward S.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/crossley-reflector] Holden, the first director, learned that Crossley wanted to sell the well-regarded Common 36-inch telescope.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/crossley-reflector] Holden and Crossley exchanged letters and worked out transferring the telescope.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/crossley-reflector] Crossley was very impressed by the enhanced observing conditions at Mount Hamilton, and, in April 1895, he formally telegraphed the Lick that he would donate the telescope.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/crossley-reflector] Funds had to be raised to ship the telescope to California, which included money from various donors including many small donations from members of the public, as well as donated services.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/crossley-reflector] For example, the heavy parts of the telescope were shipped by The Southern Pacific Company at no cost, a service of over US$1,000 (at that time).
[src:argentine-national-observatory/crossley-reflector] Converting the buying power of 1896 dollars to 2017 dollars, that can be estimated at US$12,000.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/crossley-reflector] The reflecting telescope type was scarcely used in the United States at the time of the donation, with a noted exception being the work of H.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/crossley-reflector] Observations by Keeler helped establish large reflecting telescopes with metal-coated glass mirrors as astronomically useful, as opposed to earlier cast speculum metal mirrors.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/crossley-reflector] Great refractors were still in vogue, but the Crossley reflector foreshadowed the success of large reflectors in the 1900s.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/crossley-reflector] Other large reflectors followed, such as the *Harvard 60-inch Reflector* (152 cm), also with a mirror by A.A.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/crossley-reflector] Common, or the *1 Meter Spiegelteleskop* (39.4 inch reflector) of the Hamburg Observatory.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/crossley-reflector] At this time the 72-inch Leviathan of Parsonstown was the largest by aperture, but it used a metal mirror.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/crossley-reflector] Despite the accomplishments of reflectors under Herschel, in the 19th century much of the astronomical community used relatively small refractors, often just a few inches in aperture, save for a few larger ones.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/crossley-reflector] In 1898 Keeler became director of the Lick Observatory, succeeding Edward S.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/crossley-reflector] Keeler used the Crossley, which had challenged earlier astronomers due to its unstable mounting and unsuitable locations, to take a series of photographs of spiral nebulae which were later identified as other galaxies.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/crossley-reflector] He observed that these spiral nebulae outnumbered all the other hazy objects detectable at that time via telescope.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/crossley-reflector] The detail and resolution of his photographs were remarkable at the time and are still.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/crossley-reflector] After Keeler died unexpectedly in 1900, William W.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/crossley-reflector] Campbell, now Lick Observatory's astronomer-in-charge, assigned Assistant Astronomer Charles Dillon Perrine "to take charge of all duties in connection with the Crossley" including completing Keeler's photography of nebulae and clusters including publishing Keeler's nebulae photographs.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/crossley-reflector] Perrine completed Keeler's observation of the near-Earth asteroid 433 Eros, for the determination of the solar parallax.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/crossley-reflector] Perrine further significantly reconstructed the telescope from 1902 to 1905.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/crossley-reflector] Perrine would use the rebuilt Crossley to great effect in discovering eight comets and the sixth and seventh satellites (moons) of Jupiter.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/crossley-reflector] The Crossley was so effective that when Perrine became the director of the Argentine National Observatory in Cordoba in 1909, he established a program to install a 60-inch (76-centimeter) reflecting telescope in Argentina.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/crossley-reflector] At that time it would have been equal to the largest reflector on Earth.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/crossley-reflector] After a world war and national economic crisis the "Perrine telescope" at the Bosque Alegre astrophysical station (Estación Astrofísica de Bosque Alegre) was inaugurated in 1942 when it was the largest reflector in South America.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/crossley-reflector] In the 1930s, the Crossley mirror was tested with vapor-deposited aluminum for reflection, rather than coated by using a silver metal precipitated out of a solution.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/crossley-reflector] Nicholas Mayall was a long time user of the Crossley and added a slitless spectrograph to extend its usefulness in the face of larger telescopes.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/crossley-reflector] NGC 185 was first photographed between 1898 and 1900 by James Edward Keeler with the Crossley reflector.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/crossley-reflector] Other early photographic imaging targets, dating to 1899, include GC 4628 and GC 4964, GC 4373, and the "Ring nebula in Lyra." Keeler notes that in a 4-hour exposure, 16 new nebulae were found, seeing objects that were normally much to hard to make out with the reflector visually.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/crossley-reflector] As an example of its performance, Keeler noted that in a two-hour exposure of the "cluster in Hercules" made on July 13, 1899, he could count 5400 stars on the photograph.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/crossley-reflector] He noted how with long exposure on this telescope the "swarms of minute stars" that gave it a nebulous look were resolved.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/crossley-reflector] In 1900, Assistant Astronomer Charles Dillon Perrine took hundreds of photographs of the near-Earth asteroid 433 Eros for the determination of the solar parallax.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/crossley-reflector] From 1902 to 1905, after significant reconstruction by Perrine, he discovered eight comets and the sixth and seventh satellites (moons) of Jupiter.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/crossley-reflector] Mayall's Object was discovered by American astronomer Nicholas U.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/crossley-reflector] Mayall of the Lick Observatory on 13 March 1940, using the Crossley reflector.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/crossley-reflector] In 1990, the Crossley was used to test the photometric detection of exoplanets, including around the star CM Draconis.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/crossley-reflector] In 1978, the Crossley was used to observe planetary nebulae with photoelectric photometry (spectrophotometry).
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] Córdoba was founded as a settlement on 6 July 1573 by Spanish conquistador Jerónimo Luis de Cabrera, who named it after the Spanish city of Córdoba.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] It was one of the early Spanish colonial capitals of the region of present-day Argentina (the oldest Argentine city is Santiago del Estero, founded in 1553).
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] The National University of Córdoba, the oldest university of the country, was founded in 1613 by the Jesuit Order, and Córdoba has earned the nickname *La Docta* ("the learned").
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] The campus belongs today to the historical museum of the National University of Córdoba, which has been the second-largest university in the country since the early years of the 20th century (after the University of Buenos Aires), in number of students, faculty, and academic programs.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] Córdoba is also known for its historical movements, such as the Cordobazo of May 1969 and *La Reforma del '18* (known as the University Revolution in English) of 1918.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] In 1570 the Viceroy of Peru, Francisco de Toledo, entrusted the Spanish settler Jerónimo Luis de Cabrera with the task of founding and populating a settlement in the Punilla Valley.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] Cabrera sent an expedition of 48 men to the territory of the Comechingones.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] He divided the principal column that entered through the north of the provincial territory at Villa María.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] The expedition of one hundred men set foot on what today is Córdoba on 24 June 1573.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] Cabrera called the nearby river San Juan (today Suquía).
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] The settlement was officially founded on 6 July of the same year and named *Córdoba de la Nueva Andalucía*, possibly in honour of ancestors of the founder's wife, who originally came from Córdoba, Spain.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] The foundation of the city took place on the left bank of the river on the advice of Francisco de Torres.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] The area was inhabited by aboriginal people called Comechingones, who lived in communities called *ayllus*.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] After four years, having repelled attacks by the aborigines, the settlement's authorities moved it to the opposite bank of the Suquía River in 1577.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] The Lieutenant Governor at the time, Don Lorenzo Suárez de Figueroa, planned the first layout of the city as a grid of 70 blocks.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] Once the city core had been moved to its current location, the population stabilized.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] The city's economy blossomed due to trade with the cities in the north.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] In 1599, the religious order of the Jesuits arrived in the settlement.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] They established a Novitiate in 1608 and, in 1610, the Colegio Maximo, which became the University of Córdoba in 1613 (today National University of Córdoba), the fourth-oldest in the Americas.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] The local Jesuit church remains one of the oldest buildings in South America and contains the Monserrat Secondary School, a church, and residential buildings.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] To maintain such a project, the Jesuits operated five *Reducciones* in the surrounding fertile valleys, including Caroya, Jesús María, Santa Catalina, Alta Gracia and Candelaria.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] The farm and the complex (started in 1615, had to be vacated by the Jesuits following the 1767 decree by King Charles III of Spain that expelled the Jesuit order from the continent.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] Franciscans then operated the Jesuits' foundations until 1853, when the Jesuits returned to the Americas.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] Nevertheless, the university and the high-school were nationalized a year later.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] Each estancia has its own church and set of buildings, around which towns grew, such as Alta Gracia, the closest to the Block.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] In 1776, King Carlos III created the Viceroyalty of the Río de la Plata, in which Córdoba stays in 1785 as the Government Intendency of Córdoba, including the current territories of the provinces of Córdoba, La Rioja and the region of Cuyo.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] According to the 1760 census, the population of the city was 22,000 inhabitants.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] During the May Revolution in 1810, the widespread opinion of the most notable citizens was of continuing respecting the orders of Fernando VII, attitude assumed by the local authorities, which led to the Liniers Counter-revolution.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] This position was not shared by the Dean Gregorio Funes, who was adhering to the revolutionary ideas, beside supporting contact with Manuel Belgrano and Juan José Castelli.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] In March 1816, the Argentine Congress met in Tucumán for an independence resolution.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] Córdoba sent Eduardo Pérez Bulnes, Jerónimo Salguero de Cabrera, José Antonio Cabrera, and to the Canon of the cathedral Michael Calixto of the Circle, all of them of autonomous position.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] The 1820s belonged to caudillos, since the country was in full process of formation.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] Until 1820 a central government taken root in Buenos Aires existed, but the remaining thirteen provinces felt that after 9 July 1816 what had happened it was simply a change of commander.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] The Battle of Cepeda pitted the commanders of the Littoral against the inland forces.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] Finally, the Federales obtained the victory, for what the country remained since then integrated by 13 autonomous provinces, on the national government having been dissolved.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] From this way the period known like about the Provincial Autonomies began.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] From this moment the provinces tried to create a federal system that was integrating them without coming to good port, this mainly for the regional differences of every province.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] Two Córdoba figures stood out in this period: Governor Juan Bautista Bustos, who was an official of the Army of the North and in 1820 was supervised by the troops quartered in Arequito, a town near Córdoba, and his ally and later enemy, General José María Paz.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] In 1821, Bustos repelled the invasion of Córdoba on the part of Francisco Ramírez and his Chilean ally, General José Miguel Carrera.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] The conflict originated in a dispute with the power system that included the provinces of Buenos Aires, Córdoba and Santa Fe; according to the 1822 census the total population of Córdoba was of 11,552 inhabitants.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] At the end of the 19th century the process of national industrialization began with the height of the economic agro-exporting model, principally of meats and cereals.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] This process is associated with the European immigration who began to settle the city, generally possessing the education and enterprising capacity appropriate for the development of industry.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] At the beginning of the 20th century the city had 90,000 inhabitants.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] The city's physiognomy changed considerably following the construction of new avenues, walks and public squares, as well as the installation of an electrified tram system, in 1909.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] In 1918, Córdoba was the epicentre of a movement known as the University Reform, which then spread to the rest of the Universities of the country, Americas and Spain.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] The development of the domestic market, the British investments that facilitated European settlement, the development of the railways on the pampas rapidly industrialized the city.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] Córdoba's industrial sector first developed from the need to transform raw materials such as leather, meats and wool for export.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] In 1927, the Military Aircraft Manufacturer (FMA) was inaugurated.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] The facility would become one of the most important in the world after World War II with the arrival of German technical personnel.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] From 1952, its production began to diversify, to constitute the base of the former Institute Aerotécnico, the state-owned company Aeronautical and Mechanical Industries of the State (IAME).
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] Córdoba was chosen as the site of The *Instituto Aerotécnico* that later became the *Fábrica Militar de Aviones*.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] It employed the Focke Wulf men until President Juan Perón was ousted by a coup in 1955.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] Córdoba, according to the census of 1947, had almost 400,000 inhabitants (a quarter of the province's total).
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] Subsequent industrial development led thousands of rural families to the city, doubling its population and turning Córdoba into the second largest city in Argentina, after Buenos Aires, by 1970.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] The city's population and economic growth moderated, afterwards, though living standards rose with the increase in the national consumption of Córdoba's industrial products, as well as the development of other sectors of economic activity.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] Córdoba's current economic diversity is due to a vigorous services sector and the demand for agro-industrial and railway equipment and, in particular, the introduction of U.S. and European automakers after 1954.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] 1295 29 December 1893, the limits of the city of Córdoba are delineated in the northern part, South, East and West located to 12 km (7 mi) from San Martín Square which means that the common land has 24 km (15 mi) from side.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] The city, adjoins in the northern territory with Colón Department summarizing a total surface of 562.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] The city is located in the plain of the Humid Pampa, to the east of the oriental cord of Córdoba Hills or Sierras Chicas, also known as the Sierras Cordobesas, which has an average height of 550 m.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] It spreads at the foot of the mount, on both banks of the River Suquía, and flows into the San Roque reservoir; from there, the Primero River goes east into the plains surrounding the city of Córdoba.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] Once inside the city, the *La Cañada* stream meets the Rio Primero near the city centre area.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] Two kilometers to the east, *Isla de los Patos* (Ducks Island) was repopulated with ducks and swans in the 1980s.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] It was reported in March 2006 that a large number of ducks had died due to unspecified causes.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] Pollution caused by chemical waste is suspected as the cause, but avian influenza is also being investigated.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] Beyond the city limits, the river flows towards the Algarrobos swamp and ends its course on the southern coast of the Mar Chiquita (or Mar de Ansenuza) salt lake.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] All in all, the river has a length of approximately 200 km (124 mi) and carries, on average, 9.7 m³/s, with minimum of 2 m³/s and maximum of 24 m³/s with a peak during the summer months.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] Pollution of the water and of the riverbank is a major environmental issue in Córdoba.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] Periodic cleaning operations are carried out to increase the quality of the water and to preserve the viability of fishing, both in the San Roque reservoir area and downstream.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] The climate of the city of Córdoba, and that of most of the province, is humid subtropical (*Cwa*, according to the Köppen climate classification), moderated by the Pampas winds, cold winds that blow from the South-western quadrant, which originate in Antarctica.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] Summers run from late November till early March, and bring days between 28 °C (82 °F) and 33 °C (91 °F) and night between 15 °C (59 °F) and 19 °C (66 °F) with frequent thunderstorms.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] By late February or early March, nights start getting cooler and, in March, highs average 27 °C (81 °F) and lows 15 °C (59 °F); after cold fronts, lows below 10 °C (50 °F) and highs below 20 °C (68 °F) are recorded in this month.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] April is significantly drier already; highs reach 24 °C (75 °F) on average and lows 12 °C (54 °F), creating very pleasant conditions.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] In some years, temperatures can approach or even reach the freezing point in late April; however, heat waves of up to 33 °C (91 °F) are still possible, but nights are rarely as hot as in the summer.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] May usually brings the first frosts, and very dry weather, with under 20 mm (1 in) of rain expected.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] Highs average 21 °C (70 °F) and lows average 8 °C (46 °F); however, when cold waves reach the area, highs may stay below 8 °C (46 °F) and lows can be well below freezing.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] Winter lasts from late May till early September, and bring average highs of 18 °C (64 °F) and lows of 4 °C (39 °F).
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] However, strong northwesterly winds downsloping from the mountains can bring what is known as "Veranito" (little summer) with highs of up to 30 °C (86 °F) or more and dusty, windy weather (but dry, pleasant nights) for 2–3 days.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] Snowfall is very rare in the city, but more frequent in the outskirts where the Sierras begin ; sleet may fall every once in a while.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] The record low temperature for Córdoba is −8.3 °C (17.1 °F).
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] In June, only 3.5 mm (0.1 in) of rain are expected, compared to 168 mm (6.6 in) in January.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] Spring is extremely variable and windy: there may be long stretches of cool, dry weather and cold nights followed by intense heat waves up to 38 °C (100 °F), followed by the most severe thunderstorms with hail and high winds.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] It is not unusual to see temperatures drop 20 °C (36 °F) from one day to another, or to have frost following extreme heat.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] Drought is most common in this season, when the normal summer rainfall arrives later than expected.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] By October, days are warm at 26 °C (79 °F) but nights remain cold at 11 °C (52 °F), by late November, the weather resembles summer weather with cooler nights.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] The wealthier suburbs west of the city are located at slightly higher altitudes, which allows cool breezes to blow in the summer, bringing drier, comfortable nights during hotter periods, and more regular frost in the winter.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] Generally speaking, Córdoba's daytime temperatures are very slightly warmer than Buenos Aires' but nighttime lows are usually cooler, especially in the winter.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] This, combined with a lower humidity and the possibility of fleeing to higher altitudes minutes away from the city centre, makes the climate a bit more comfortable than in the capital.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] The variations or thermal extents are greater than in Buenos Aires, and lower in annual rainfall: 750 mm (30 in) / year.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] The annual average temperature calculated during the 20th century was 18 °C.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] In January, the hottest month of the austral summer, the average maximum is 31 °C and the minimum 17 °C.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] In July, the coldest month of the year, the average temperatures are between 19 °C and 3 °C.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] In winter it is very frequent that temperatures rise above 30 °C, due to the influence of the wind Zonda.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] Due to the extension of the metropolitan area, there exists a difference of 5 °C between the central area and the Greater Córdoba.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] The central district, a dense high-rise area is located in a depression, and it is the core of an important heat island.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] In addition the city presents a phenomenon of smog, but not so dense as to present health concerns.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] The largest ethnic groups in Córdoba are Italians/Italian Argentine and Spaniards/Spanish Argentine (mostly Galicians and Basques/Basque Argentine).
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] Waves of immigrants from other European countries arrived in the late 19th and early 20th centuries.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] From the rest of Western Europe came immigrants from Switzerland, Germany, United Kingdom, Ireland and Scandinavia (especially Sweden).
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] Other Europeans also arrived from nations such as Croatia, Poland, Hungary, Russia, Romania, Ukraine, Armenia and the Balkans (especially Greece, Serbia and Montenegro).
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] By the 1910s, 43 percent of the city population was non-native Argentine after immigration rates peaked.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] Important Lebanese, Syrian and Armenian communities have had a significant presence in commerce and civic life since the beginning of the 20th century.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] Most immigrants, regardless of origin, settled in the city or around Greater Córdoba.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] However, in the early stages of immigration, some formed settlements (especially agricultural settlements) in different parts of the city, often encouraged by the Argentine government and/or sponsored by private individuals and organizations.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] Córdoba is the second largest city in the country in population and concentrates 40.9% of the Córdoba Province population of 3,216,993 inhabitants and represents almost 3.3% of the Argentine population, which is 43 million inhabitants.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] Driven by migration both domestic and from abroad, the city's rate of population growth was an elevated 3.2% annually from 1914 to 1960; but, it has been declining steadily since then, and has averaged around 0.4% a year, since the national census of 2001.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] According to the last provincial census of 2008, the city has 1,315,540 inhabitants, representing an increase of 3.78% with regard to the 1,267,521 registered during the national census of 2001.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] Greater Córdoba is the metropolitan area of the city of Córdoba, a union of medium localities of the department Colón, from the north to the south.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] Greater Córdoba is the second-largest urban agglomeration in Argentina in both population and surface area.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] The growth of the metropolitan area was not equal in all directions, it spreads approximately up to 50 km (31 mi) to the northwest of the Córdoba city centre in a thin succession of small localities.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] This is almost the maximum distance from the Buenos Aires city center to the most distant of its metropolitan area points; whereas in the rest of the cardinal points it comes to 15 km (9 mi).
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] The city receives a constant flow of students from the northeastern and southwestern regions of Argentina and of other South American countries, owed principally to the National University of Córdoba, which increases gradually the city population.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] Córdoba grows constantly, expanding especially towards the southern areas of Alta Gracia and Villa Carlos Paz.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] Green spaces include different types of spaces, from small squares, up to urban, green linear parks of different scales as the river Suquia, bicycle pathways and highways.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] The surface area of green spaces supported by the Municipality of Córdoba adds up to approximately 1645 hectares.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] The historical centre is shaped by quadrangular blocks of some hundred thirty meters of side.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] The disposition of the neighborhoods and principal avenues is radial.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] From the city centre district large avenues lead out to the most peripheral neighborhoods.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] In conformity with demographic growth, the city has expanded principally to the northwest and to the southeast, following the trace of the National Route 9.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] The governor, Juan Schiaretti, finalized the Circunvalaciónon on 6 July 2019, with completing the building of the last 2,8 km of the route from La Cañanada to Fuerza Aerea.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] This ended the construction of the 47 km long ring road motorway, which takes almost 34 minutes to complete.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] Córdoba is home to one of the most important financial districts in South America.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] The district is home to the Bank of Córdoba and other private banking institutions.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] Sightseeing places include San Martín Square, the Jesuit Block (declared UNESCO World Heritage Site) and the Genaro Pérez Museum.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] The streets mostly follow a regular checkerboard pattern, and the main thoroughfares are Vélez Sarsfield, Colón, General Paz, Dean Funes Avenue, and 27 April Street.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] The point of origin of the city is San Martin Square, surrounded by the Municipality and Central Post Office.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] Downtown Córdoba is home to large shopping malls, notably Patio Olmos.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] This mall is the result of a massive regeneration effort, recycling and refurbishing the west side old warehouses into elegant offices and commercial centres.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] An important cultural point of interest is the Palacio Ferreyra, a mansion built in 1916 based on plans by the French architect, Ernest Sanson.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] The Ferreyra palace was converted into the Evita Perón Museum of Fine Arts (the city's second) in 2007.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] Located at the corner of Hipólito Yrigoyen and Chacabuco Avenues, it has now been restored and adapted to house the city's principal art gallery.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] New Córdoba has a number of important avenues such as *Yrigoyen* and *Vélez Sarsfield*.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] Most of the university students in this growing city live in this neighbourhood, and a recent construction boom has been transforming this upscale area into the fastest-growing section in the city.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] Ciudad Universitaria is a district located in the southern area of the city, next to the 17 hectares (42 acres) Sarmiento Park, the city's most important one.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] The Universidad Nacional de Córdoba (UNC) has most of its facilities in this area.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] The UNC was the first university built in Argentina, founded by Jesuits around 1622.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] The Universidad Nacional de Córdoba is also famous for the "Reforma Universitaria", a student-led protest that started in March 1918 in the Medical School, in which the students rebelled against the prevailing university system.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] This was an old anachronistic system in which professors were authoritarian and inefficient, with a religiously-oriented curriculum.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] Eventually this revolt led to a more secular curriculum and some significant re-structuring of the university government.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] The distinctive nature of the movement derived not only from its radical demands, but also from its extremist tactics, the level of sophistication of its organization, and its major continental impact.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] In fact, the Reform Movement rapidly spread from Córdoba to Lima (1919), Cuzco (1920), Santiago de Chile (1920), and Mexico (1921).
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] Another important university, the UTN, dedicated to the teaching of engineering sciences, is located in this part of the city.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] There is also a gym and football stadium and tennis courts for the students.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] The *Córdoba Zoo* is located in this district.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] Located about 6 km (4 mi) from downtown Córdoba is the Cerro de Las Rosas.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] This very affluent neighborhood is famous for its schools, shops and educational institutions.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] This neighborhood's economic activity centers around Rafael Núñez Avenue, a long wide road that stretches for a few kilometers and has restaurants, boutiques, banks and other shops.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] Over the last decade, this neighborhood has experienced steady growth; however, some of its most affluent inhabitants have moved to gated communities for security reasons.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] Some of these communities, such as "Las Delicias" and "Lomas de los Carolinos", are in the old Camino a La Calera.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] The Córdoba public transport system includes trains, buses, trolleybuses and taxis.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] Long-distance buses reach most cities and towns throughout the country.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] The city is served by the nation's third-largest airport, Ingeniero Ambrosio L.V.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] Taravella International Airport, a vibrant airport with domestic flights within Argentina as well as to Brazil, Chile, the Dominican Republic, Panama, Paraguay, Peru and Spain on 15 passenger airlines.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] Buses are, by far, the most popular way of transportation around Córdoba Province.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] There are many different companies that provide long distance, short distance and urban services.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] They all have their own prices, that are not cheap compared to the rest of Argentina.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] Córdoba is one of the Provinces with higher transportation rates.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] Rail transport in Córdoba has commuter and long-distance services, all operated by the state-owned Trenes Argentinos.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] From the Mitre railway station trains depart for Villa María while the Tren de las Sierras connects the district of Alta Córdoba with Cosquín.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] From Retiro station in Buenos Aires, trains reach Córdoba twice a week with an estimated journey time of 18 hours.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] Many people choose the train because of the low cost, but it takes almost twice the time that would take to do the same trip by bus (around eight hours).
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] The Tren de las Sierras is a tourist service that crosses part of the Valle de Punilla, Quebrada del Río Suquía and borders the Dique San Roque's Lake.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] It has two services per day with an additional service on weekends.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] It takes between 2 and 3 hours to go from Alta Córdoba Station to Cosquín.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] Córdoba has two railway stations, the Córdoba (Mitre) originally built by the Central Argentine R. in 1886.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] That station has been an intermediate stop for trains to Tucumán, successively operated by Ferrocarriles Argentinos and then by private consortiums such as Ferrocentral.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] The other station is Alta Córdoba, built and operated by British-owned Córdoba North Western in 1891, and currently the terminus of Tren de las Sierras.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] The Argentine government had planned to build a high-speed train between Buenos Aires-Rosario-Córdoba.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] It would eventually join Córdoba and Buenos Aires, with an intermediate stop in Rosario, in about 3 hours at speeds of up to 350 km/h (220 mph).
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] Originally scheduled to be started in 2008, with its inauguration in 2010, the project was finally cancelled in December 2012.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] The total cost of the rail had been estimated at US$4,000,000,000.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] French company Alstom, which had won the tender to build the high-speed rail, admitted paying bribes to the Argentine authorities.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] On 10 December 2007 it was announced that a consortium of Iecsa/Gela companies was to build a US$1.1 billion metro system in Córdoba.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] In April 2008, President Cristina Fernández de Kirchner, signed the project into law.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] The project has been suspended since 2012.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] The average amount of time people spend commuting with public transit in Córdoba, for example to and from work, on a weekday is 64 min.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] 13.8% of public transit riders ride for more than two hours every day.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] The average amount of time people wait at a stop or station for public transit is 21 min, while 43% of riders wait for over 20 minutes on average every day.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] The average distance people usually ride on a single trip with public transit is 5 km, while 4% travel for over 12 km in a single direction.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] Since World War II, Córdoba has been developing a versatile industrial base.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] The biggest sectors is car and car parts manufacturing: Renault has a factory which produces a range of cars and Volkswagen has a factory specialized in the production of gearboxes.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] The capital goods company CNH Industrial has also a factory in the city.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] The legal service Novadios was founded in 2008 in this city.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] Many suppliers (both local and foreign) manufacture car parts for these operations.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] Additionally, in 2017–2018, Nissan and Mercedes-Benz began the production of their new pickup truck at the local Renault factory.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] Railway construction (Materfer) and aircraft construction (Fábrica Militar de Aviones) were once significant employers, but their activities have greatly diminished.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] Furthermore, there are some textile, heavy and chemical industries (e.g.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] Areas around Córdoba produce vast amounts of agricultural products, and some of these are processed around the city.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] Additionally, the province is one of the main producers of agricultural machinery in the country, although most of these operations are not in the city itself.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] Candy company Arcor is headquartered in the city.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] Córdoba has been considered the technological centre of Argentina.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] The Argentine *spaceport* (Centro Espacial Teófilo Tabanera), where satellites are being developed and operated for CONAE, is located in the suburb of Falda del Carmen.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] The software and electronic industries are advancing and becoming significant exporters; among the leading local employers in the sector are Motorola, Vates, Intel, Electronic Data Systems, and Santex América.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] The city also has a service-based economy focused on retail, professional services and financial services, where the main local player is credit card provider Tarjeta Naranja.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] It has recently emerged as a start-up hub with a growing number of angel investors, in part due to the availability of people with technology-oriented skills.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] Association football is the most popular sport in Córdoba as well as in Argentina.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] Several leagues and divisions compete in the local championship annually.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] The city currently has three representatives in the Argentine First Division, Talleres, Belgrano, and Instituto, and also one in the second, Racing de Córdoba.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] Estadio Mario Alberto Kempes hosted 8 matches in the 1978 FIFA World Cup.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] Basketball is the second-most popular sport in Córdoba.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] Asociación Deportiva Atenas is the most popular club, and one of the most successful in Argentina, having won the National League (LNB) seven times, and being three times winner of the South American League.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] Córdoba was one of the host cities of the official Basketball World Cup for its 1967 and 1990 editions.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] Cordoba was also a host for the 2002 FIVB Men's Volleyball World Championship and organized the UCI BMX World Championships in 2000.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] Rugby union is also a very popular sport in Córdoba, which has close to 20 teams with many divisions.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] Tala Rugby Club, Club La Tablada, Córdoba Athletic Club (one of the oldest clubs in Argentina and founded by the British who worked in the building of the Argentine Railroads around 1882), Jockey Club Córdoba, and Club Universitario de Córdoba are some of the most prestigious teams.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] Córdoba is one of the strongest rugby places in Argentina, and is the home of many international players.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] Many of the great players in Argentina and Italy began their careers in the Córdoba's rugby clubs.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] In tennis, since 2019, the Córdoba Open is also held at the "Polo Deportivo Kempes", a sports complex next to Estadio Mario Alberto Kempes.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] Golf and tennis are also very popular; notable players who started playing in Córdoba include Ángel "Pato" Cabrera and Eduardo "Gato" Romero (b.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] 1954) in golf and David Nalbandian in tennis.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] The Argentine stage of the World Rally Championship has been run near Córdoba since 1984.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] Motorsport events also take place at Autódromo Oscar Cabalén, such as TC2000 but has hosted Stock Car Brasil and Formula Truck.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] Córdoba has long been one of Argentina's main educational centers, with 6 universities and several postsecondary colleges.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] Students from the entire country, as well as neighbouring countries attend the local universities, giving the city a distinct atmosphere.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] The National University of Córdoba, established since 1613, is the 4th oldest in the Americas and the first in Argentina.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] It has about 105,000 students, and offers degrees in a wide variety of subjects in the sciences, applied sciences, social sciences, humanities and arts.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] The Catholic University of Córdoba is the oldest private university in Córdoba, it has nearly 10,000 students.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] The Aeronautic University Institute, run by the Argentine Air Force, offers degrees in aeronautical, telecommunications and electronic engineering, as well as information systems, accounting, logistics and administration.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] The Instituto Tecnológico Córdoba was created jointly by the six universities located in the city to support technological development in the region.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] Furthermore, the Universidad Siglo 21 and Universidad Blas Pascal are private universities in the city.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] The Air Force Academy and the Air Force NCOs School are both located in the city outskirts.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] There is an Italian international school, Escuela Dante Alighieri.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] The area once had a German school, Deutsche Schule Cordoba.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] Museums include the Caraffa Fine Arts Museum, founded in 1916, and the Evita Fine Arts Museum, founded in 2007.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] The Paseo del Buen Pastor cultural center opened in 2007.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] Downtown's Córdoba Cathedral, the Córdoba Cabildo, and the Plaza San Martín all serve as active public gathering spaces.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] The Jesuit Block (Manzana Jesuítica) is one of the most important historical and cultural landmarks in Córdoba, Argentina.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] Located in the city center, it was declared a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 2000 for its outstanding value as a religious, educational, and architectural complex.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] The Jesuits, members of the Society of Jesus founded by St.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] Ignatius of Loyola in 1534, arrived in Córdoba in 1599.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] They were granted land on the southern edge of the new city, where they established a convent, cloisters, workshops, and gardens.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] In 1613, they founded the Colegio Máximo, which later developed into the National University of Córdoba, the first university in the Southern Cone and the oldest in Argentina.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] The Jesuit Block also became the center of a network of rural estancias (farms), which supported the order’s educational and missionary work through a model of economic self-sufficiency.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] Today, parts of the Jesuit Block are open to the public, offering visitors a chance to explore Córdoba’s academic and spiritual heritage.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] Highlights include the church, the historic cloisters, and the Monserrat School.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] The Historical Museum of the National University of Cordoba displays manuscripts, early scientific collections, and items related to the university’s history.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] Guided tours often highlight underground structures and archaeological findings, adding a sense of mystery to the visit.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] The Jesuit Block is also connected to modern history: Pope Francis (then Jorge Mario Bergoglio) lived in Córdoba during the 1960s as a young Jesuit priest, spending a period of study and reflection in the residence linked to the complex.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] The Jesuit Block showcases a harmonious blend of colonial Baroque architecture and functional design rooted in Jesuit ideals of austerity and utility.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] Key structures include the Iglesia de la Compañía de Jesús, built between 1640 and 1671, notable for its adobe and stone construction and wooden ceiling made using indigenous techniques.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] The urban layout integrates religious, educational, and residential elements, reflecting the Jesuit commitment to community and holistic education.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] The entire complex was restored following its UNESCO designation in 2000, ensuring preservation of original masonry, woodwork, and archaeological features.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] The Colegio Nacional de Monserrat and the residences and cloisters reflect a mix of Spanish colonial and local Criollo styles.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] Underground tunnels, which likely served as ventilation and escape routes, add a layer of architectural intrigue.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] The Jesuit Block has had a lasting cultural, educational, and religious impact on Argentina and Latin America.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] It laid the foundation for the National University of Córdoba, the oldest in Argentina, which played a central role in the 1918 University Reform Movement that shaped higher education across Latin America.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] The Jesuit system of self-sustaining rural estancias linked to the block pioneered a model of regional development.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] The site also holds spiritual significance, as it was a formative location for Pope Francis, who lived and studied there during a pivotal period in the 1960s.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] Its inscription as a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 2000 elevated international awareness of Jesuit cultural contributions in the Southern Cone.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-argentina] Today, the complex continues to function as a symbol of Córdoba’s academic excellence and religious heritage.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-province-argentina] Córdoba is the second-most populous Argentine province, with 3,978,984 inhabitants, and the fifth by size, at about 165,321 km2 (63,831 sq mi).
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-province-argentina] Almost 41% of its inhabitants reside in the capital city, Córdoba, and its surroundings, making it the second most populous metro area in Argentina.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-province-argentina] Before the Spanish conquista the region now called Córdoba Province was inhabited by indigenous groups, most notably the Comechingones and Sanavirones.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-province-argentina] Once settled in Upper Peru, the Spaniards searched for a route to the Río de la Plata port in the Atlantic Ocean to transport the Peruvian gold and silver to Europe.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-province-argentina] In 1783, seven years after the consolidation of the Viceroyalty of the Río de la Plata, the Intendency of Córdoba became the capital of what now includes the La Rioja, Mendoza, San Juan, and San Luis Provinces, dividing the former Tucumán Intendency in two.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-province-argentina] Rafael de Sobremonte was its first governor, when Córdoba City had 38,800 inhabitants.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-province-argentina] After the May Revolution in 1810, Governor Juan Gutiérrez de la Concha joined a meeting that decided to ignore the authority of the Buenos Aires Junta.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-province-argentina] Francisco Ortiz de Ocampo attacked the city and executed the leaders of the opposition, among whom was Santiago de Liniers, leader of the resistance during the British invasions of the Río de la Plata.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-province-argentina] Led by Juan Bautista Bustos after 1820, Córdoba struggled for control of the nation with Buenos Aires; the United Provinces of South America had neither legislative nor executive branches at the time.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-province-argentina] Córdoba sought a federal organization of the provinces while Rivadavia pushed for a centralised government in Buenos Aires.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-province-argentina] For 15 years, the province was submerged in internal revolts that started to stabilize in 1868 under the provisional government of Félix de la Peña.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-province-argentina] During the presidency of Sarmiento an astronomic observatory (1871) and the Faculty of Physical Sciences and Mathematics (1873) were inaugurated.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-province-argentina] The creation of the railways and the consequent immigration brought a second wave of population growth to Córdoba.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-province-argentina] From 1887 on, several agricultural colonies (San Francisco, Marcos Juárez, etc.) emerged, while former rest-point Fraile Muerto (Bell Ville), Ferreira (Villa María) and Los Luceros (Río Segundo), on the route to Buenos Aires, became agricultural, commercial and industrial centers, respectively.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-province-argentina] The University Reform movement, which originated in Córdoba in 1918, was influential not only in Argentina but throughout South America.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-province-argentina] After World War II, many foreign workers and workers from other provinces in Argentina were attracted to Córdoba's industrial development, led by the expansion of the car industry.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-province-argentina] It was during Arturo Frondizi's presidency (1958–1962) that most new auto industries settled in the city of Córdoba and its surroundings.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-province-argentina] As in the rest of the country, Peronist groups emerged in 1955 following the coup that removed Juan Perón from office.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-province-argentina] These Peronist groups, together with other socialist and anarchist groups, began opposing Argentina's third military dictatorship that began in 1966.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-province-argentina] Worker and student participation in politics grew due to the widespread discontent with the appointed governor's hard-line stance, culminating in the violent May, 1969, popular revolt known as the *Cordobazo*.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-province-argentina] This revolt, mirrored by the *Rosariazo* and others in several parts of the country, undermined the power of dictator Juan Carlos Onganía and ultimately led to his ouster by more moderate military factions.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-province-argentina] Córdoba, located just north of the geographical center of the nation, is Argentina's fifth-largest province.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-province-argentina] West of this chain, two valleys contain most of the tourist spots in the province: the Calamuchita valley in the south and the Punilla Valley in the north, home of scenic towns such as Villa Carlos Paz, Cosquín, La Cumbre, and La Falda.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-province-argentina] West of these valleys, the Sierras Grandes form the highest chain in the province: their altitude increases gradually to form a plateau of 2,000 to 2,300 meters (6,600 to 7,500 ft) known as Pampa de Achala, culminating with Cerro Champaqui on the western part, at 2,790 meters (9,150 feet).
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-province-argentina] West of these mountains, there is an impressive drop towards the valley known as Valle de Traslasierra, and across the valley, the Sierras Orientales reach an altitude of 1,650 meters (5,410 feet) at Cerro Yerba Buena.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-province-argentina] In the northeast corner of the province, a natural depression forms an extensive salt lake called Mar Chiquita Lake.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-province-argentina] The actual surface of the lake is 6,000 km2 (2,300 sq mi), but during extended dry periods (such as in the 1980s) it can be a third of that, with much higher salinity.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-province-argentina] The southeastern part of the province is home to numerous ponds, lakes, and wetlands.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-province-argentina] The climate of the province is predominantly temperate, with some regional variations.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-province-argentina] Generally speaking, summers are hot and humid, falls are pleasant, winters are extremely dry with strong variations in temperature, and springs are windy and variable.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-province-argentina] Monthly precipitation during this season ranges from 90 to 120 mm (3.5 to 4.7 in).
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-province-argentina] Nights are noticeably cooler in March, which is also the rainiest month, and April often brings very pleasant weather with highs around 23 °C (73 °F) and lows around 11 °C (52 °F).
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-province-argentina] Starting in May, rainfall is low, with less than 25 mm (0.98 in) monthly during the winter.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-province-argentina] Frost arrives in late April in the south, and late May in the north.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-province-argentina] The air is often humid in winter, and thick fog is very common.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-province-argentina] Snowfall is very rare, almost unheard of in the northeast, but snowstorms can occur: in 2007, between 10 and 20 cm (4 and 8 in) covered a significant part of the region, and temperatures plummeted to -9 °C in most areas (16F).
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-province-argentina] Spring is very variable, alternating between very intense heat waves and cool weather periods with severe thunderstorms, hail and strong winds.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-province-argentina] Total precipitation is over 850 mm (33 in) along the border with Santa Fe and diminishes to about 700 mm (28 in) in the west, reaching a minimum of about 600 mm (24 in) in the southernmost part of the province.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-province-argentina] This climate allows eastern Córdoba to be the nation's main producer of soybeans and peanuts, and a large producer of maize and dairy products.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-province-argentina] The foothills of the Sierras are known for their pleasant weather: summer days are slightly cooler and the air feels much drier despite high precipitation; winters are much drier with less fog and less wind, and more pleasant sunny days.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-province-argentina] The eastern slopes of the sierras experience the highest precipitation: usually about 900 mm (35 in), with some spots averaging up to 1,200 mm (47 in) which fall exclusively in the form of very heavy thunderstorms in the summer.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-province-argentina] Snowfall occurs more frequently in the sierras, but is rarely heavy due to the dryness of the air.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-province-argentina] The weather in the Pampa de Achala is very variable because of the high altitude: generally speaking, the strong radiation provides pleasant summer afternoons, but temperatures at night can be very cold.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-province-argentina] Frost can happen throughout the year, and winters are extremely dry with nights well below 0 °C (32 °F).
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-province-argentina] Temperatures well under −15 °C (5 °F) have been recorded, and snowfall is very common but in small quantities due to the lack of precipitation during the colder months.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-province-argentina] Summer thunderstorms can be very violent, bringing large hail, frequent lightning and high winds.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-province-argentina] The region of Traslasierra is known for its markedly warmer climate: summer temperatures often reach well over 35 °C (95 °F) and nights are often very warm.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-province-argentina] Fall arrives later than elsewhere, and spring arrives earlier as well.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-province-argentina] Winters are pleasant, with common light frost followed by very pleasant afternoons reaching about 19 °C (66 °F).
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-province-argentina] Precipitation is even more seasonal than in the rest of the province, falling exclusively in the summer and reaching a total of 500 to 700 mm (20 to 28 in).
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-province-argentina] The warmer climate is excellent for the production of Mediterranean agricultural products such as figs, olives and grapes.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-province-argentina] The extreme northern and northwestern areas of the province are located on the transition between the temperate Pampa and the subtropical Gran Chaco: summers are consistently longer and warmer than in other areas, and extremes of 40 °C (104 °F) are more frequent.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-province-argentina] Winters are shorter, with night temperatures similar to those further south, but with warmer days.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-province-argentina] This is the most drought-prone area of the province, with rainfall as little as 400 mm (16 in) annually.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-province-argentina] According to the 2022 Argentine national census, the Province of Córdoba has 3,978,984 inhabitants.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-province-argentina] Córdoba has the second-largest provincial economy in Argentina, behind only the Province of Buenos Aires.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-province-argentina] As in most places, the majority of GDP is produced by services (financial, educational, medical, professional, etc.).
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-province-argentina] In the past, the province had significant call centers, but these have mostly been moved to lower-wage locations.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-province-argentina] The province is among the most visited in Argentina (mostly by domestic travelers) because of its hilly landscapes, pleasant weather, "fun" reputation, and cultural offerings.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-province-argentina] In particular, cities like Villa Carlos Paz, Villa General Belgrano, Cosquín and La Cumbrecita attract a large number of tourists.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-province-argentina] This supports a large hospitality industry with hotels, restaurants, bars and resorts.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-province-argentina] Around three million tourists, both foreign and Argentine, visit Córdoba every year.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-province-argentina] The province has 500,000 hotel beds, including hostels, tourist farms, and other types of accommodation.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-province-argentina] There are four five-star hotels, of which three are located in Córdoba City (Sheraton Cordoba Hotel, Holiday Inn, Interplaza), and one on the hills at Punilla Valley (El Castillo).
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-province-argentina] Important festivities include the Cosquín National Folk Music Festival, and the Jesús María Folk and Taming Festivals.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-province-argentina] Call centers flourished in the province in the past but have mostly been moved to lower-wage locations.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-province-argentina] They were instead replaced by service centers from technology companies, starting with Motorola several years ago, and many of these have evolved into software and technology development centers.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-province-argentina] Current players in that industry include Intel, Mercado Libre, Santex, Globant and a vast (and growing) number of small, specialized providers which have organized under the banner of the "Cordoba Technology Cluster".
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-province-argentina] The capital city has been named one of Latin America's major startup ecosystems, with several active angel investors, incubators and a well-educated talent pool supported by local universities.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-province-argentina] Beginning around 1955, foreign investment in Córdoba's automotive, agricultural machinery and food processing industries further added to its industrial profile.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-province-argentina] Currently, Renault and FIAT produce cars in the provincial capital, with additional investments underway from Nissan, Renault and Mercedes-Benz to jointly produce a pickup truck starting in 2017–2018.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-province-argentina] Volkswagen operates a large manufacturing facility which produces and exports gearboxes.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-province-argentina] In total, 250 manufacturers of either motor vehicles or auto parts operate in Córdoba, making it Argentina's "motor province".
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-province-argentina] Several facilities produce agricultural machinery (tractors, harvesters, etc.) - these are often located in small and medium cities outside the capital.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-province-argentina] Chemical manufacturing is centered around Rio Tercero.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-province-argentina] Food processing is another strength of the province, with the multinational candy and snack manufacturer Grupo Arcor headquartered in Arroyito and one of the largest oil producers in the world (Aceitera General Deheza, or AGD) headquartered in General Deheza.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-province-argentina] The cities of Villa Maria and San Francisco are major cheese production centers, while Oncativo and Colonia Caroya are known for the production of sausages and Villa General Belgrano for its beer.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-province-argentina] Historically, cheap, sweet wine was produced in the north of the province; in the last decade, a number of more sophisticated wineries have found that the province has locations with excellent climate and soil for wine production (especially in hilly areas).
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-province-argentina] Industry represents 17% of the province's income, and the energy production that supports it is based mainly on 15 hydroelectric dams (2.35 billion kW/hours a year) and the Embalse nuclear power plant (600 MWe of capacity, about 2 billion kWh, yearly).
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-province-argentina] Agriculture and livestock provide 10% of the province's output, well above the national average.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-province-argentina] The agriculture is centered on soybeans, wheat and maize, and other cereals.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-province-argentina] Cattle and sheep enjoy the grass of Córdoba's green hills.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-province-argentina] The province provides the nation with 15% of its beef production and 28% of its dairy output.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-province-argentina] Mining includes many different minerals, and construction material such as marble and lime.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-province-argentina] Uranium is also extracted to feed Argentina's three atomic plants.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-province-argentina] Córdoba is connected by rail with Buenos Aires, Rosario, Mendoza and Tucumán.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-province-argentina] Taravella International Airport, known as Pajas Blancas, handles international and domestic air traffic, with several daily flights to Buenos Aires and some daily flights to Santiago de Chile, Mendoza, Bariloche, Rosario, São Paulo, Panama City, Rio de Janeiro and Lima.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-province-argentina] Furthermore, Air Europa operates direct flights to Madrid.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-province-argentina] Córdoba has a unicameral legislature elected by universal suffrage.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-province-argentina] Until December 2001, the legislature was bicameral (a Chamber of Deputies and a Senate), but following the 2001 constitutional reform, this division was abolished.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-province-argentina] The unified legislature is made up of 70 members: 26 elected to represent each of the provincial departments and 44 elected by the people of the province as a whole and assigned by a proportional system.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-province-argentina] The Constitution of Córdoba forms the formal law of the province.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-province-argentina] The head of government is the governor, accompanied by a vice-governor who presides over the legislature and may fill the governor's place in certain cases.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-province-argentina] Like the legislators, the governor and vice-governor are elected for a four-year term, and can be re-elected for one consecutive term.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-province-argentina] Córdoba has long been a bastion of the centrist Radical Civic Union, but in 1999 the Justicialist José Manuel de la Sota was elected governor, succeeded by fellow Peronist Juan Schiaretti in 2007.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-province-argentina] In Argentina, the most important law enforcement organization is the Argentine Federal Police but the additional work is carried out by the Córdoba Provincial Police.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/córdoba-province-argentina] The province is divided in 26 regions, or departments (Spanish: *departamentos*), listed below with their regional capitals.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] Sarmiento grew up in a poor but politically active family that paved the way for many of his future accomplishments.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] Between 1843 and 1850, he was frequently in exile, and wrote in both Chile and in Argentina.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] His most famous work was *Facundo*, a critique of Juan Manuel de Rosas, that Sarmiento wrote while working for the newspaper *El Progreso* during his exile in Chile.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] As president, Sarmiento championed intelligent thought—including education for children and women—and democracy for Latin America.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] He also modernized and developed train systems, a postal system, and a comprehensive education system.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] He spent many years in ministerial roles on the federal and state levels where he travelled abroad and examined other education systems.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] Sarmiento died in Asunción, Paraguay, at the age of 77 from a heart attack.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] Today, he is respected as a political innovator and writer.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] Miguel de Unamuno considered him among the greatest writers of Castilian prose.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] Sarmiento was born in Carrascal, a poor suburb of San Juan, Argentina, on 15 February 1811.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] His father, José Clemente Quiroga Sarmiento y Funes, had served in the military during the wars of independence, returning prisoners of war to San Juan.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] His mother, Doña Paula Zoila de Albarracín e Irrazábal, was a very pious woman, who lost her father at a young age and was left with very little to support herself.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] As a result, she took to selling her weaving in order to afford to build a house of her own.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] On 21 September 1801, José and Paula were married.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] They had 15 children, 9 of whom died young; Domingo was the only son to survive to adulthood.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] Sarmiento was greatly influenced by his parents, his mother who was always working hard, and his father who told stories of being a patriot and serving his country, something Sarmiento strongly believed in.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] At the age of four, Sarmiento was taught to read by his father and his uncle, José Eufrasio Quiroga Sarmiento, who later became Bishop of Cuyo.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] Another uncle who influenced him in his youth was Domingo de Oro, a notable figure in the young Argentine Republic who was influential in bringing Juan Manuel de Rosas to power.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] Though Sarmiento did not follow de Oro's political and religious leanings, he learned the value of intellectual integrity and honesty.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] He developed scholarly and oratorical skills, qualities which de Oro was famous for.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] In 1816, at the age of five, Sarmiento began attending the primary school *La Escuela de la Patria*.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] He was a good student, and earned the title of First Citizen (*Primer Ciudadano*) of the school.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] After completing primary school, his mother wanted him to go to Córdoba to become a priest.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] He had spent a year reading the Bible and often spent time as a child helping his uncle with church services, but Sarmiento soon became bored with religion and school, and got involved with a group of aggressive children.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] Sarmiento's father took him to the Loreto Seminary in 1821, but for reasons unknown, Sarmiento did not enter the seminary, returning instead to San Juan with his father.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] In 1823, the Minister of State, Bernardino Rivadavia, announced that the six top pupils of each state would be selected to receive higher education in Buenos Aires.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] Sarmiento was at the top of the list in San Juan, but it was then announced that only ten pupils would receive the scholarship.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] The selection was made by lot, and Sarmiento was not one of the scholars whose name was drawn.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] Like many other nineteenth-century Argentines prominent in public life, he was a Freemason.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] In 1826, an assembly elected Bernardino Rivadavia as president of the United Provinces of the Río de la Plata.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] This action roused the ire of the provinces, and civil war was the result.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] Support for a strong, centralized Argentine government was based in Buenos Aires, and gave rise to two opposing groups.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] The wealthy and educated of the Unitarian Party, such as Sarmiento, favored centralized government.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] In opposition to them were the Federalists, who were mainly based in rural areas and tended to reject European mores.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] Numbering figures such as Manuel Dorrego and Juan Facundo Quiroga among their ranks, they were in favor of a loose federation with more autonomy for the individual provinces.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] Opinion of the Rivadavia administration was divided between the two ideologies.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] For Unitarians like Sarmiento, Rivadavia's presidency was a positive experience.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] He set up a European-staffed university and supported a public education program for rural male children.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] He also supported theater and opera groups, publishing houses and a museum.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] These contributions were considered as civilizing influences by the Unitarians, but they upset the Federalist constituency.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] Common laborers had their salaries subjected to a government cap, and the *gauchos* were arrested by Rivadavia for vagrancy and forced to work on public projects, usually without pay.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] In 1827, the Unitarians were challenged by Federalist forces.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] After the resignation of Rivadavia, Manuel Dorrego was installed as governor of Buenos Aires province.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] He quickly made peace with Brazil but, on returning to Argentina, was overthrown and executed by the Unitarian general Juan Lavalle, who took Dorrego's place.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] However, Lavalle did not spend long as governor either: he was soon overthrown by militias composed largely of *gauchos* led by Rosas and Estanislao López.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] By the end of 1829 the old legislature that Lavalle had disbanded was back in place and had appointed Rosas as governor of Buenos Aires.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] The first time Sarmiento was forced to leave home was with his uncle, José de Oro, in 1827, because of his military activities.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] José de Oro was a priest who had fought in the Battle of Chacabuco under General San Martín.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] Together, Sarmiento and de Oro went to San Francisco del Monte de Oro, in the neighbour province of San Luis.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] He spent much of his time with his uncle learning and began to teach at the only school in town.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] Later that year, his mother wrote to him asking him to come home.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] Sarmiento refused, only to receive a response from his father that he was coming to collect him.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] His father had persuaded the governor of San Juan to send Sarmiento to Buenos Aires to study at the College of Moral Sciences (*Colegio de Ciencias Morales*).
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] Soon after Sarmiento's return, the province of San Juan broke out into civil war and Facundo Quiroga invaded Sarmiento's town.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] Unable to attend school in Buenos Aires due to the political turmoil, Sarmiento chose to fight against Quiroga.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] He joined and fought in the unitarian army, only to be placed under house arrest when San Juan was eventually taken over by Quiroga after the battle of Pilar.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] He was later released, only to join the forces of General Paz, a key unitarian figure.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] Fighting and war soon resumed, but, one by one, Quiroga vanquished the main allies of General Paz, including the Governor of San Juan, and in 1831 Sarmiento fled to Chile.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] He did not return to Argentina for five years.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] At the time, Chile was noted for its good public administration, its constitutional organization, and the rare freedom to criticize the regime.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] As a form of freedom of expression, Sarmiento began to write political commentary.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] In addition to writing, he also began teaching in Los Andes.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] Due to his innovative style of teaching, he found himself in conflict with the governor of the province.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] He founded his own school in Pocuro as a response to the governor.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] During this time, Sarmiento fell in love and had an illegitimate daughter named Ana Faustina, who Sarmiento did not acknowledge until she married.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] In 1836, Sarmiento returned to San Juan, seriously ill with typhoid fever; his family and friends thought he would die upon his return, but he recovered and established an anti-federalist journal called *El Zonda*.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] The government of San Juan did not like Sarmiento's criticisms and censored the magazine by imposing an unaffordable tax upon each purchase.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] Sarmiento was forced to cease publication of the magazine in 1840.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] He also founded a school for girls during this time called the Santa Rosa High School, which was a preparatory school.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] In addition to the school, he founded a Literary Society.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] It is around this time that Sarmiento became associated with the so-called "Generation of 1837".
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] This was a group of activists, who included Esteban Echeverría, Juan Bautista Alberdi, and Bartolomé Mitre, who spent much of the 1830s to 1880s first agitating for and then bringing about social change, advocating republicanism, free trade, freedom of speech, and material progress.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] Though, based in San Juan, Sarmiento was absent from the initial creation of this group, in 1838 he wrote to Alberdi seeking the latter's advice; and in time he would become the group's most fervent supporter.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] In 1840, after being arrested and accused of conspiracy, Sarmiento was forced into exile in Chile again.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] It was en route to Chile that, in the baths of Zonda, he wrote the graffiti "On ne tue point les idées," an incident that would later serve as the preface to his book *Facundo*.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] Once on the other side of the Andes, in 1841 Samiento started writing for the Valparaíso newspaper *El Mercurio*, as well working as a publisher of the *Crónica Contemporánea de Latino América* ("Contemporary Latin American Chronicle").
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] In 1842, Sarmiento was appointed the Director of the first Normal School in South America; the same year he also founded the newspaper *El Progreso*.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] During this time he sent for his family from San Juan to Chile.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] In 1843, Sarmiento published *Mi Defensa* ("My Defence"), while continuing to teach.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] And in May 1845, *El Progreso* started the serial publication of the first edition of his best-known work, *Facundo*; in July, *Facundo* appeared in book form.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] Sarmiento began his visit to the United States with a mere six hundred dollars from the Chilean government, much of the former allowance being expended on preceding journeys to Africa and Europe.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] As a result, he planned to visit as much of the country as financially possible and end his journey in Havana, where he would take the role of a teacher and journalist to earn more funds to finance future journeys across the American continents.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] However, Sarmiento discarded this plan upon meeting Santiago Arcos, a Chilean journalist who agreed to defraying the expenses of subsequent journeys.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] Sarmiento initially could not locate or find any information about the whereabouts of Arcos, but the two eventually met in Philadelphia.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] During his visit to the United States, Sarmiento visited major locations such as Boston, Washington, D.C., and New Orleans.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] Sarmiento would again travel to the United States from the years 1865 to 1868 when serving as Argentina's minister plenipotentiary to the country.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] Based on his travels, he wrote the book *Viajes por Europa, África, y América* which was published in 1849.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] In 1848, Sarmiento voluntarily left to Chile once again.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] During the same year, he met widow Benita Martínez Pastoriza, married her, and adopted her son, Domingo Fidel, or Dominguito, who would be killed in action during the War of the Triple Alliance at Curupaytí in 1866.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] Sarmiento continued to exercise the idea of freedom of the press and began two new periodicals entitled *La Tribuna* and *La Crónica* respectively, which strongly attacked Juan Manuel de Rosas.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] During this stay in Chile, Sarmiento's essays became more strongly opposed to Juan Manuel de Rosas.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] The Argentine government tried to have Sarmiento extradited from Chile to Argentina, but the Chilean government refused to hand him over.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] In 1850, he published both *Argirópolis* and *Recuerdos de Provincia* (Recollections of a Provincial Past).
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] In 1852, Rosas's regime was finally brought down.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] Sarmiento became involved in debates about the country's new constitution.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] In 1854, Sarmiento briefly visited Mendoza, just across the border from Chile in Western Argentina, but he was arrested and imprisoned.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] Upon his release, he went back to Chile.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] But in 1855 he put an end to what was now his "self-imposed" exile in Chile: he arrived in Buenos Aires, soon to become editor-in-chief of the newspaper *El Nacional*.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] He was also appointed town councillor in 1856, and 1857 he joined the provincial Senate, a position he held until 1861.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] It was in 1861, shortly after Mitre became Argentine president, that Sarmiento left Buenos Aires and returned to San Juan, where he was elected governor, a post he took up in 1862.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] It was then that he passed the *Statutory Law of Public Education*, making it mandatory for children to attend primary school.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] It allowed for a number of institutions to be opened including secondary schools, military schools and an all-girls school.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] While governor, he developed roads and infrastructure, built public buildings and hospitals, encouraged agriculture and allowed for mineral mining.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] He resumed his post as editor of *El Zonda*.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] In 1863, Sarmiento fought against the power of the *caudillo* of La Rioja and found himself in conflict with the Interior Minister of General Mitre's government, Guillermo Rawson.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] Sarmiento stepped down as governor of San Juan to become the Plenipotentiary Minister to the United States, where he was sent in 1865, soon after the assassination of President Abraham Lincoln.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] Moved by the story of Lincoln, Sarmiento ended up writing his book *Vida de Lincoln*.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] It was on this trip that Sarmiento received an honorary degree from the University of Michigan.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] A bust of him stood in the Modern Languages Building at the University of Michigan until multiple student protests prompted its removal.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] Students installed plaques and painted the bust red to represent the controversies surrounding his policies towards the indigenous people in Argentina.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] There still stands a statue of Sarmiento at Brown University.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] While on this trip, he was asked to run for President again.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] He won, taking office on 12 October 1868.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] Domingo Faustino Sarmiento was put forward as a candidate for the presidency of the nation by a group of Argentine politicians at the initiative of Colonel Lucio V.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] He won the presidency despite the maneuverings of his predecessor Bartolomé Mitre.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] Two days after his inauguration, Congress met for a brief extraordinary session, during which it approved the budget for the following year, a loan of four million pesos, and an increase in customs duties in order to finance the continuation of the Paraguayan War.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] Sarmiento served as President of Argentina from 1868 to 1874.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] According to biographer Allison Bunkley, his presidency "marks the advent of the middle, or land-owning classes as the pivot power of the nation.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] The age of the gaucho had ended, and the age of the merchant and cattleman had begun." Sarmiento sought to create basic freedoms, and wanted to ensure civil safety and progress for everyone, not just the few.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] Sarmiento's tour of the United States had given him many new ideas about politics, democracy, and the structure of society, especially when he was the Argentine ambassador to the country from 1865 to 1868.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] Europe contemplates in New England the power which in the future will supplant her."* Not only did Sarmiento evolve political ideas, but also structural ones by transitioning Argentina from a primarily agricultural economy to one focused on cities and industry.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] Historian David Rock notes that, beyond putting an end to caudillismo, Sarmiento's main achievements in government concerned his promotion of education.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] Sarmiento's focus on education became a divisive tool of his nation-building strategy.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] With this focus, he was able to build the foundation to promote the intellect of future generations and securing their prosperity.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] There was an emphasis on constructing educational buildings, and training prospective teachers.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] His emphasis on constructing these schools and promoting education served as an example for future administrations to build upon.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] By the end of his presidency, the Red Line extended 1,331 kilometres (827 mi).
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] In 1869, he conducted Argentina's first national census.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] Although the rapid expansion of the railroad promoted trade, Latin America saw a rise in inequality and an intensified pressure to drive indigenous people from their land in order to expand the economy.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] With the expansion of the railroad itself came an expansion of exploration, stimulated by the access to previously inaccessible lands.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] Sarmiento's successor, Nicolas Avellaneda, further promoted this policy.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] In the late 1870s Julio Roca, his minister of war, carried out the Conquest of the Desert.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] This war, stimulated by the expansion of Latin American railroads, was waged against the indigenous people of Southern Argentina.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] In addition to the expansion and driving out that was done by the people, the government had now officially declared its intentions.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] Following the model of displacement that had been outlined by North America, the Conquest of the Desert established the dominance of Argentina as a nation-state, and set a dangerous precedent.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] With this precedent, Argentine dominance cost the killing and displacement of the Mapuche people in the Patagonia providence.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] Though Sarmiento promoted modernization and growth that made Argentina stronger, the idea of expansion meant the expulsion and killings of indigenous peoples.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] Though Sarmiento is well known historically, he was not a popular president.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] Indeed, Rock judges that "by and large his administration was a disappointment".
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] During his presidency, Argentina conducted an unpopular war against Paraguay; at the same time, people were displeased with him for not fighting for the Straits of Magellan from Chile.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] Although he increased productivity, he increased expenditures, which also negatively affected his popularity.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] In addition, the arrival of a large influx of European immigrants was blamed for the outbreak of Yellow Fever in Buenos Aires and the risk of civil war.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] Moreover, Sarmiento's presidency was further marked by ongoing rivalry between Buenos Aires and the provinces.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] In the war against Paraguay, Sarmiento's adopted son was killed.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] Sarmiento suffered from immense grief and was thought to never have been the same again.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] On 22 August 1873, Sarmiento survived an assassination attempt while on his way to the home of Vélez Sarsfield in the city of Buenos Aires.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] As he passed through what is now the intersection of Corrientes and Maipú streets, an explosion shook the coach carriage in which he was travelling.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] Sarmiento did not hear it, as he was already deaf.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] The shooters were two Italian anarchists, the brothers Francisco and Pedro Guerri, who declared that they had been hired by men of federal caudillo Ricardo López Jordán.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] The attempt failed because Francisco Guerri's blunderbuss burst in his hand.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] Sarmiento emerged from the attack unhurt.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] A year later in 1874, he completed his term as President and stepped down, handing his presidency over to Nicolás Avellaneda, his former Minister of Education.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] It is generally accepted that Domingo Faustino Sarmiento devoted most of his efforts in government to the promotion of education, although some historians maintain that he gave at least equal importance to expanding communications throughout the country.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] In any case, the impetus given to education under the ministry of Nicolás Avellaneda was notable.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] Through the Subsidies Law of 1871—which assigned to public education inheritances without direct heirs and one eighth of the proceeds from sales of public land—the government guaranteed funding for the creation of new schools and the purchase of materials and books.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] During his presidency, and with national support, the provinces founded about 800 primary schools, bringing the total to 1,816 schools, of which 27% were private; the school population rose from 30,000 to 110,000 pupils.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] He also subsidized the first school for deaf students, which was privately run.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] Continuing the policy of his predecessor, he founded National Colleges in La Rioja, Santa Fe, San Luis, San Salvador de Jujuy, Santiago del Estero, Corrientes, San Nicolás de los Arroyos, and Rosario.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] One of his first decisions was to hold an Exposition of Arts and National Products, which was ultimately staged in 1871 in the city of Córdoba.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] The project was initially regarded as folly, but it ended up being a major success.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] It showcased textiles, tanneries, foundries, dyeworks, and agricultural products from different regions of the country.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] During his visit to the exposition, Sarmiento wore a vicuña suit made from national fabrics and also received a medal for having introduced wicker into the country.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] A large amount of agricultural and industrial machinery available for import was also promoted there.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] The exposition marked the beginning of a concern with the basic sciences, and from this impulse emerged the Academy of Sciences of Córdoba—directed by the German botanist Germán Burmeister—and the National Observatory of Córdoba, directed by the American astronomer Benjamin Gould.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] At the National University of Córdoba the Faculty of Exact, Physical and Natural Sciences was created, offering a degree in engineering.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] On 17 April 1853 he transformed his country's wine industry by introducing new French grape varieties, such as Malbec, and by creating the Quinta Agronómica of Mendoza, which later became the Faculty of Agricultural Sciences.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] Today, Malbec is one of the leading varieties in the Argentine wine market and an emblem of the country's viticulture.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] The War of the Triple Alliance against Paraguay had broken out during Mitre's presidency, and he had commanded the allied forces against that country until shortly before leaving office.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] Barely had Sarmiento assumed the presidency when the final Brazilian advance on Asunción took place, and the city was sacked by Brazilian troops.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] Paraguayan president Francisco Solano López, despite the occupation of the capital, organized a new army some distance away.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] In response, a provisional government was formed in Asunción under Argentine and Brazilian protection.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] An army formed and led mainly by Brazilians—in which the Argentines at first had some participation—set out in pursuit of Solano López in the so-called Campaign of the Hills.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] After two bloody victories over the Paraguayans, Solano López managed to escape toward the northern edge of the country, where two Brazilian divisions eventually caught up with him, defeated him, and killed him at the Battle of Cerro Corá on 1 March 1870.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] Paraguay was left devastated: depending on the source, between 50 and 90% of its total population is estimated to have died during the conflict, and it lost all the territories in dispute with its neighbors except the Chaco Boreal.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] The war also imposed an enormous cost on Argentina: first in human lives, with more than 18,000 men killed in the conflict, to which may be added the many thousands who died of cholera, including 15,000 in Buenos Aires Province alone.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] It also had a huge economic cost, as Argentina was forced to borrow until its debt reached 9,000,000 pounds sterling.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] During the last year of the war, the Colegio Militar de la Nación was founded, with the Hungarian Juan F.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] The possibility of conflict with Brazil arising from the postwar disputes led Sarmiento to modernize the navy: he founded the Naval School and incorporated several ships, thereby creating the first Argentine squadron capable of operating at a level comparable to the war fleets of Brazil and Chile.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] After the defeat of Felipe Varela, three Argentine provinces were still in federalist hands: in Córdoba, military pressure forced Governor Luque to resign, and in Corrientes a liberal revolution overthrew the federalist governor in May 1868.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] A belated federalist response was crushed by troops of the national army transferred from the Paraguayan front in defense of a government that had emerged from a coup d'état.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] Only Entre Ríos remained, where Urquiza coexisted peacefully with the national government against the wishes of many federalists: at the beginning of 1870 he had received the president at his residence in the Palacio San José and ordered that the corresponding honors be paid.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] Shortly after the end of the Paraguayan War, on 11 April 1870, General Ricardo López Jordán launched a revolution in which Urquiza was killed by the Cordoban Simón Luengo.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] López Jordán was elected governor by the legislature.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] President Sarmiento sent to Entre Ríos an army made up of divisions veteran from the Paraguayan War.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] The governor forbade those troops from entering his province, but the president ridiculed the notion that the entry of national troops into a province could be prohibited.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] When the landing took place, López Jordán ordered the general mobilization of the province.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] Sarmiento declared war on Entre Ríos, although Congress did not authorize the federal intervention in that province until August.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] Four armies advanced simultaneously into the province; the national troops—superior in arms and discipline—occupied the cities, forcing López Jordán to withdraw into the interior, where the men of Entre Ríos, mounted on better horses, held out to advantage.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] Seeking to open a new front, López Jordán invaded Corrientes Province, but on 26 January 1871 he was completely defeated in the Battle of Ñaembé; shortly afterward he fled to Brazil.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] The Entre Ríos Federal Party was destroyed, and the federalists were removed from all public offices, including priests and schoolteachers.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] In May 1873 López Jordán again rose in rebellion in his province, eventually commanding 16,000 men, well supplied with artillery and infantry.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] Sarmiento responded by placing a price on López Jordán's head—a measure rejected by Congress—and by decreeing the federal intervention of Entre Ríos.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] Three armies occupied the province under the overall command of the Minister of War, Martín de Gainza.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] Once again fighting spread throughout the province, and several Jordanist officers were shot; after a bloody defeat, López Jordán departed for Uruguay in December.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] One of Domingo Faustino Sarmiento's first measures as president of Argentina was to organize the first national census, which was carried out in 1869; it produced a result of 1,836,490 inhabitants for the country.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] Of the total, 8% were European immigrants, 70% lived in rural areas, and 71% were illiterate.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] During his presidency, immigration rose sharply with the arrival of 280,000 immigrants, who settled mainly in the city of Buenos Aires and, to a lesser extent, in agricultural colonies in the Litoral provinces.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] The rapid growth of the population in the capital created large-scale problems of housing and hygiene: in 1871 a yellow fever epidemic—probably a consequence of the war—caused the deaths of around 14,000 people in Buenos Aires.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] The entire national government fled the city, so the fight against the plague had to be carried out by a commission.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] This body ordered the creation of the La Chacarita Cemetery and in the following years the city's first water-supply and sewerage networks were established.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] As president, one of his chief transportation goals was the construction of a trans-Andean railway linking the Atlantic and the Pacific.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] To this end, the construction of the branch line from Villa María (Córdoba) to Río Cuarto was encouraged; the branch from Córdoba to Tucumán was also built, as were two short branch lines, one between Concordia (Entre Ríos) and Mercedes (Corrientes), and the other between Buenos Aires and Campana.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] The railway network grew from 573 kilometers in 1868 to 1,331 in 1874.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] Since it was planned to extend the railway from Córdoba northward, he hired the German engineer José Enrique Rauch to design the route from Salta to the Pacific coast, which decades later would become the so-called Train to the Clouds.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] During his presidency, about 5,000 km of telegraph lines were laid, promoted by the president and his minister, Vélez Sarsfield; in his 1873 message to Congress he was able to state that "the telegraph line has been completed and now runs through the whole Republic".
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] A number of ports were built, including those of Zárate and San Pedro (Buenos Aires).
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] A modern port for Buenos Aires was planned, and the country went into debt for 30 million pesos to carry out the works, but that money was squandered on minor projects.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] In 1873 the National Bank was created, which lent money at low interest or to insolvent debtors.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] The public debt—driven by the debt generated by the Paraguayan War—reached unsustainable levels, although the resulting economic crisis would not break out until the administration of his successor.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] During the first part of his administration, Foreign Minister Mariano Varela sought to pursue an almost idealistic policy regarding Paraguay's future: his well-known phrase "Victory does not confer rights" formed part of an attempt to limit the expansionist ambitions of Brazil.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] Brazil's response was to take advantage of that same policy by having the Paraguayan government protest against the Argentine occupation of Villa Occidental, opposite Asunción.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] When the Brazilian ambassador in Paraguay forced changes in the Paraguayan government, the president replaced Varela with Carlos Tejedor.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] In 1872 Brazil signed a boundary treaty with Paraguay by which it awarded itself all the disputed territory, and then supported Paraguay in defending itself against Argentine claims.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] Tejedor then began an aggressive campaign to settle the disputes as quickly as possible, leading to growing tension with Brazil.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] Relations with Chile centered on the dispute over the rights of the two countries in Patagonia.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] In 1874 it was decided that arbitration by the King of England would settle the disputes between them.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] In 1875, following his term as President, Sarmiento became the General Director of Schools for the Province of Buenos Aires.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] That same year, he became the Senator for San Juan, a post that he held until 1879, when he became Interior Minister.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] But he soon resigned, following conflict with the Governor of Buenos Aires, Carlos Tejedor.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] He then assumed the post of Superintendent General of Schools for the National Education Ministry under President Roca and published *El Monitor de la Educación Común*, which is a fundamental reference for Argentine education.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] In 1882, Sarmiento was successful in passing the sanction of Free Education allowing schools to be free, mandatory, and separate from that of religion.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] In May 1888, Sarmiento left Argentina for Paraguay.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] He was accompanied by his daughter, Ana, and his companion Aurelia Vélez.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] He died in Asunción on 11 September 1888, from a heart attack, and was buried in Buenos Aires, after a ten-day trip.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] His tomb at La Recoleta Cemetery lies under a sculpture, a condor upon a pylon, designed by himself and executed by Victor de Pol.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] Pedro II, the Emperor of Brazil and a great admirer of Sarmiento, sent to his funeral procession a green and gold crown of flowers with a message written in Spanish remembering the highlights of his life: "Civilization and Barbarism, Tonelero, Monte Caseros, Petrópolis, Public Education.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] Sarmiento was well known for his modernization of the country, and for his improvements to the educational system.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] He firmly believed in democracy and European liberalism, but was most often seen as a romantic.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] Sarmiento was well versed in Western philosophy including the works of Karl Marx and John Stuart Mill.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] He was particularly fascinated with the liberty given to those living in the United States, which he witnessed as a representative of the Peruvian government.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] He did, however, see pitfalls to liberty, pointing for example to the aftermath of the French Revolution, which he compared to Argentina's own May Revolution.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] He believed that liberty could turn into anarchy and thus civil war, which is what happened in France and in Argentina.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] Therefore, his use of the term "liberty" was more in reference to a laissez-faire approach to the economy, and religious liberty.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] Though a Catholic himself, he began to adopt the ideas of separation of church and state modeled after the US.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] He believed that there should be more religious freedom, and less religious affiliation in schools.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] This was one of many ways in which Sarmiento tried to connect South America to North America.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] Sarmiento believed that the material and social needs of people had to be satisfied but not at the cost of order and decorum.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] He put great importance on law and citizen participation.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] These ideas he most equated to Rome and to the United States, a society which he viewed as exhibiting similar qualities.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] In order to civilize the Argentine society and make it equal to that of Rome or the United States, Sarmiento believed in eliminating the caudillos, or the larger landholdings and establishing multiple agricultural colonies run by European immigrants.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] Coming from a family of writers, orators, and clerics, Domingo Sarmiento placed a great value on education and learning.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] He opened a number of schools including the first school in Latin America for teachers in Santiago in 1842: *La Escuela Normal Preceptores de Chile*.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] He proceeded to open 18 more schools and had mostly female teachers from the United States come to Argentina to instruct graduates how to be effective when teaching.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] Sarmiento's belief was that education was the key to happiness and success, and that a nation could not be democratic if it was not educated.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] "An ignorant people will always choose Rosas.".
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] His views on the South American Indians have been more controversial, with some scholars arguing Sarmiento's views reflected the racism of his day.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] For example, in the periodical *El Nacional,* dated 25 November 1857, Sarmiento wrote: “Will we be able to exterminate the Indians?
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] For the savages of America, I feel an invincible repugnance that I cannot cure.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] Those scoundrels are not anything more than disgusting Indians that I would hang if they reappeared.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] Lautaro and Caupolicán are dirty Indians, because that's how they are all.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] Incapable of progress, their extermination is providential and useful, sublime and great.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] The impact of Domingo Faustino Sarmiento is most obviously seen in the establishment of 11 September as Panamerican Teacher's Day which was done in his honor at the 1943 Interamerican Conference on Education, held in Panama.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] Today, he is still considered to be Latin America's teacher.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] In his time, he opened countless schools, created free public libraries, opened immigration, and worked towards a Union of Plate States.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] His impact was not only on the world of education, but also on Argentine political and social structure.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] His ideas are now revered as innovative, though at the time they were not widely accepted.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] He was a self-made man and believed in sociological and economic growth for Latin America, something that the Argentine people could not recognize at the time with the soaring standard of living which came with high prices, high wages, and an increased national debt.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] There is a building named in his honor at the Argentine embassy in Washington D.C.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] Today, there is a statue in honor of Sarmiento in Boston on the Commonwealth Avenue Mall, between Gloucester and Hereford streets, erected in 1973.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] There is a square, *Plaza Sarmiento* in Rosario, Argentina.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/domingo-f-sarmiento] One of Rodin's last sculptures was that of Sarmiento which is now in Buenos Aires.
[src:argentine-national-observatory/enrique-gaviola] Asteroid 2504 Gaviola is named after him.
